  "transcript": {
    "language": "en",
    "is_generated": true,
    "segments": [
      {
        "start": 0.1,
        "duration": 4.7,
        "text": "For thousands of years, people have"
      },
      {
        "start": 2.0,
        "duration": 7.0,
        "text": "written about huge swarms of locusts,"
      },
      {
        "start": 4.8,
        "duration": 6.3,
        "text": "appearing out of nowhere, eating entire"
      },
      {
        "start": 9.0,
        "duration": 4.3,
        "text": "fields of crops, and then just"
      },
      {
        "start": 11.1,
        "duration": 4.3,
        "text": "disappearing just as quickly. What"
      },
      {
        "start": 13.4,
        "duration": 4.8,
        "text": "causes something like that to happen?"
      },
      {
        "start": 15.4,
        "duration": 6.7,
        "text": "The answer is resources."
      },
      {
        "start": 18.2,
        "duration": 7.6,
        "text": "All living things need resources to"
      },
      {
        "start": 22.2,
        "duration": 5.8,
        "text": "survive and reproduce. But what exactly"
      },
      {
        "start": 25.8,
        "duration": 4.8,
        "text": "is a resource? Well, resource is"
      },
      {
        "start": 28.0,
        "duration": 5.8,
        "text": "anything an organism needs to live. Some"
      },
      {
        "start": 30.6,
        "duration": 6.5,
        "text": "resources come from living things like"
      },
      {
        "start": 33.8,
        "duration": 5.4,
        "text": "food. We call them biotic factors. While"
      },
      {
        "start": 37.0,
        "duration": 5.5,
        "text": "others come from non-living parts of the"
      },
      {
        "start": 39.1,
        "duration": 7.4,
        "text": "environment like water, air, shelter,"
      },
      {
        "start": 42.6,
        "duration": 7.3,
        "text": "and space, we call them abiotic factors."
      },
      {
        "start": 46.6,
        "duration": 6.2,
        "text": "When organisms have enough of these"
      },
      {
        "start": 49.8,
        "duration": 7.8,
        "text": "resources, they are more likely to stay"
      },
      {
        "start": 52.8,
        "duration": 6.9,
        "text": "healthy and grow and produce offsprings."
      },
      {
        "start": 57.7,
        "duration": 6.6,
        "text": "And when many organisms have enough"
      },
      {
        "start": 59.7,
        "duration": 7.7,
        "text": "resources, their population can grow."
      },
      {
        "start": 64.3,
        "duration": 6.0,
        "text": "But there's an important catch. Most"
      },
      {
        "start": 67.4,
        "duration": 5.9,
        "text": "resources are limited. They're not"
      },
      {
        "start": 70.3,
        "duration": 5.8,
        "text": "available in an endless supply. Think"
      },
      {
        "start": 73.3,
        "duration": 6.0,
        "text": "about it. A field, for example, can only"
      },
      {
        "start": 76.1,
        "duration": 6.4,
        "text": "grow so much food. A pond can only hold"
      },
      {
        "start": 79.3,
        "duration": 6.4,
        "text": "so much water. And a forest can only"
      },
      {
        "start": 82.5,
        "duration": 4.9,
        "text": "have so many places to live. So the"
      },
      {
        "start": 85.7,
        "duration": 3.8,
        "text": "question is, what happens when a"
      },
      {
        "start": 87.4,
        "duration": 5.6,
        "text": "population gets bigger and bigger, but"
      },
      {
        "start": 89.5,
        "duration": 6.5,
        "text": "the amount of resources stays the same?"
      },
      {
        "start": 93.0,
        "duration": 5.4,
        "text": "To answer that question, let's imagine a"
      },
      {
        "start": 96.0,
        "duration": 5.4,
        "text": "small group of rabbits living in a"
      },
      {
        "start": 98.4,
        "duration": 7.2,
        "text": "meadow. At first, there is plenty of"
      },
      {
        "start": 101.4,
        "duration": 6.2,
        "text": "grass, water, and space for all of them."
      },
      {
        "start": 105.6,
        "duration": 4.9,
        "text": "The rabbits have enough to eat, so many"
      },
      {
        "start": 107.6,
        "duration": 6.0,
        "text": "survive and have babies, and so the"
      },
      {
        "start": 110.5,
        "duration": 4.7,
        "text": "rabbit population starts to grow. But as"
      },
      {
